author: {'steamid': '76561198090513887', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 30, 'playtime_forever': 435, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 435, 'last_played': 1460239655}
review:
Vanilla isn't just the name of a cat, but a perfect way to describe this game, and there's nothing wrong with that. If you enjoy a story about a guy running a bakery and interacting with various cat girls in a variety of ways, this title is right up your alley. If you're looking for something more, you'd best steer clear of this one. This is a textbook example of playing it safe, so you won't find anything here, aside from some cute dialog with some decent art direction in general and in the H-scenes.

That being said, it came out at a time where the western audience wasn't that familiar with this type of content, so it's been overhyped as a result of it. It isn't good, it isn't bad. It's just... vanilla.

author: {'steamid': '76561198415781696', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 3, 'playtime_forever': 494, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 494, 'last_played': 1636269297}
review: Despite being one man, the developer of this game really knows what his fans want. On Friday, I had burned my hand with flaming oil and stayed eight straight hours in a neglectful "healthcare" facility that took eight hours to bandage my recently singed flesh. This left me with very limited use of my left hand, thus rendering me unable to play most games as they tend to require two hands. This hero of a developer kept his clientele in mind, and made it so this game could easily be played with one hand. I can tell just by that design choice that this is an upstanding Christian man who had developed a wholesome Christian game. Obviously this game was designed for people with limited mobility such as myself, as I cannot think of any other reason why this game should be played with one hand. These design choices lead me to believe that there is still hope left for humanity, 10/10.

author: {'steamid': '76561199213743706', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 41, 'playtime_forever': 3576, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 3576, 'last_played': 1697769092}
review:
Two more to the collection...

[h1] Introduction [/h1]

Nekopara Vol.2 is the sequel to the Vol.1, developed by NEKO WORKs, and it's pretty much of the same, but with some twists. So, lets take a deeper look into this game.

[h1] Worldbuilding [/h1]

The worldbuilding remained essentially the same, save for some small additions. This time, though, the new elements were introduced through organic dialogue instead of lenghty exposition dumps, which is an improvement over the first game. It's not surprising, though, because there isn't much to introduce at this point, because the first game took care of most of the worldbuilding elements in the nekoverse.

[h1] The plot [/h1]

As a slice-of-life story, there isn't much to mention here, but I noticed a shift on the narrative focus of the story. It went from a pastry chef who wanted to start his own business to a pastry chef who started building his own harem (we all knew where this would go anyways). This time, there weren't any plotholes or contrivances to speak of, so, another improvement. The overall tone of the game remained consistent, and the tonal shifts felt organic and natural. The pacing was also good.

[h1] The characters [/h1]

This time, the game focuses on the characters of Coconut and Azuki. One thing I didn't mention in my review of Vol. 1 is that the catgirls, except Chocola and Vanilla, who are from mixed breeds, are based on a specific kind of breed, Coconut being a Maine Coon (which would explain her physique, because Maine Coons are huge), and Azuki being a Munchkin (which would explain her petite frame). Honestly, given the precedent, I didn't expect characters undergoing character arcs, but, surprisingly, there are. Coconut's character arc was setup in the first game (notice that in Extra, she called Kashou "onii-chan" but in Vol.1 she called him "Kashou-sama", which at first, indicated maturity, which, as I saw, wasn't the case). She realized (not without powerful and endearing drama) that she was pretending to be someone that she wasn't. Her core flaw was her impatience, because she wanted to become a capable adult catgirl as fast as possible, but she was able to embrace her true self and become happier because of it. I's a basic character arc, but it is consistent with her characterization and worked well. Azuki also did a bit of growing up, but not in the same level as Coconut. So far, in terms of character writing, Coconut is the best one. Azuki is a total tsundere, by the way, and Shigure's brother complex is somehow worse than in the first game.

[h1] Presentation [/h1]

There is nothing to add about art direction, sound design, character artstyle, animations, soundtrack, voice acting and H-scene quality, because they remained unchanged from the first game. The only difference I found is that now the game provides an option to pet the catgirls. They make really cute sounds when petted, and they look adorable. And not only you can pet the catgirls. You can also touch their boing-boing and caress their tummies, and they make from cute noises to lewd sounds, depending on where are you touching them.

In conclusion:

[b] Pros: [/b]

-Tiny but appreciated improvements across the board.
-It wouldn't be a catgirl game without the option of petting them.
-Coconut's character arc was satisfying.

[b] Cons: [/b]

-H-scenes are still at 30 fps.
-At 11 hours, is still a bit too short for the price.

This game saw some improvements over the first one, but there are some things that need improvement. That said, it's a good thing that this game remained consistent whether be in the story or in the presentation, and the characters are still endearing, which is a must in this type of stories. And the addition of a character arc, however basic, is a breath of fresh air to the story overall. With all that being said, this is a soild recommendation for slice-of-life enjoyers, but, like the first game, it's wise to wait for a discount to buy the game, so you can get more for your money.

[hr][/hr]

[b] Note: [/b] Coconut is so freaking hot and sexy, but also has her cute and funny moments, and she has an arc. She has the complete package, and that's why she is my favorite catgirll from the bunch.

[h1] 9/10 [/h1]

Jika Anda membaca VN Nekopara sebelumnya, maka tentu saja Anda sudah tahu tentang apa yang satu ini. Kualitas seni, BGM, dan VA-nya luar biasa seperti biasa. Gim ini murni layanan penggemar, tetapi Anda sudah tahu itu. Jika kalian mencari plot yang lebih dalam, kalian bisa mencoba yang lain. Tetapi jika Anda menikmati banyak layanan penggemar dan menikmati game Nekopara sebelumnya, selama Anda menyukai Nekos dan menikmati kisah romansa harem Slice of Life yang imut, Anda akan menyukai game ini juga.

author: {'steamid': '76561197992548148', 'num_games_owned': 1466, 'num_reviews': 50, 'playtime_forever': 211, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 211, 'last_played': 1696316099}
review:
[h1] Can be an Adult Game [/h1]

Nekopara Vol 2 is technically the third game in the franchise, but it's volume two because it's a continuation from one. We still follow Kashou and his bakery with his sister Shigure and the six cat girls in the Minaduki Family. In this game we primarily focus on Coconut and Azuki and their relationship with Kashou. There are some good moments in this game, but ultimately out of a few things, the story doesn't progress that far, but it is still a good narrative driven game. Just like the previous games, it's all narrative. You do not control the game at all. It is a really good game to continue the story. Do not start the game here, buy Vol 1 before playing this. Vol 0 isn't necessary unless you want to know more about the Catgirls.


[h1] The game isn't an adult game without buying the adult patch from Steam or other ways. It doesn't change what happens in the game, you just see adult content. Honestly in the end, the adult content is just okay. It is still censored. [/H1]

[b] Grade A

author: {'steamid': '76561197999629349', 'num_games_owned': 2195, 'num_reviews': 277, 'playtime_forever': 108, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 108, 'last_played': 1497122664}
review:
Greetings everyone, Kiba Snowpaw here, your furry ambassador from the icy realm of the north. As a well-versed gamer, anime enthusiast, and avid manga reader since the '80s, I've kickstarted and supported numerous indie games and projects on Patreon, Kickstarter, and Bandcamp. I've dedicated countless hours and thousands of dollars to bring these beloved projects to life. Today, I'm here to talk about a gem among the wealth of visual novels out there: NEKOPARA Vol. 2.

üéÆ Gameplay üéÆ

Upon opening NEKOPARA Vol. 2, I felt like I had been whisked away to a wintery world, not unlike my own, but filled with charming catgirls. The whimsical combination of visual novel elements, gentle humor, and catgirl drama has been masterfully crafted. The storytelling in this game is the cat's pajamas, my friends. It's a rollercoaster of emotions that took me on the wildest ride of my life! üé¢üò∫

üò∏ Character Development üò∏

As a seasoned anime and manga aficionado, the character development in NEKOPARA Vol. 2 is something I could really sink my teeth into. The dynamics between the catgirls are rich, engaging, and at times, hilarious! ü§£ Each character, from Vanilla's cool demeanor to Chocola's bubbly personality, Maple's assertiveness, Cinnamon's innocence, Coconut's ambition, and Azuki's maturity, brings a unique flavor to the story that kept me paw-sitively riveted. The transformations these characters undergo, their interactions, the camaraderie, and the drama are worth every second spent in this game.

üé® Art and Animation üé®

The visuals in NEKOPARA Vol. 2 are breathtaking. The artwork is vibrant, the animation is fluid, and the character designs are absolutely stunning. It's like stepping into a world crafted with meticulous attention to detail, filled with stunning landscapes, picturesque settings, and anthropomorphic cats that you can't help but fall in love with. I must say, the fur-tastic designs really hit me right in the wolf-heart! üê∫üíñ

üéº Music and Voice Acting üéº

The sound design in NEKOPARA Vol. 2 is impeccable. From the uplifting beats to the serene melodies, the music complements the atmosphere perfectly. The voice acting is top-notch as well, capturing the unique personalities of the characters with impressive accuracy. Each catgirl's voice resonated with their individual characteristics, giving the characters life and making them feel like real, relatable beings.

üìù Story üìù

As an experienced gamer who has ventured through countless worlds, the narrative of NEKOPARA Vol. 2 stands out as one of the most engaging and immersive. The plot is layered with complexities, filled with humor, heartbreak, and the occasional fluff that we furries crave! üêæ

The game presents the protagonist, Kashou, a young man who has left his life of luxury to follow his passion: opening a patisserie. His life takes an unexpected turn when two catgirls, Chocola and Vanilla, follow him to his new life, leading to a tale filled with hilarity, drama, and emotional moments.

üíñ The Impact üíñ

NEKOPARA Vol. 2 has left a profound impact on me. It's not just about the relationship between humans and their catgirl companions, but it's also about the bonds we share, the dreams we chase, and the obstacles we overcome. It's a heartwarming reminder that we're not so different from these adorable catgirls, each of us unique, each with our quirks, ambitions, and insecurities.

üéâ The Verdict üéâ

To say that NEKOPARA Vol. 2 is just a game would be an understatement. It's an experience, a journey that draws you in and holds you tight. It's a furry tale that warms even the coldest of ice wolf hearts like mine. Whether you're a furry, a gamer, or just someone looking for a fantastic story, I wholeheartedly recommend NEKOPARA Vol. 2. It gets a solid 10 out of 10 ice crystals from me. ‚ùÑÔ∏èüíô

Here's to gaming, anime, manga, and of course, the wonderful world of furries. Stay frosty, my friends! üê∫üå®Ô∏èüéÆ

review:
Als absoluter Nekopara-Vol.2-Fan kann ich sagen, dass dieses Spiel eine gro√üartige Fortsetzung des Nekopara-Universums ist. Es setzt die Geschichte der Nekos und Kashou fort und f√ºgt neue Charaktere hinzu, die genauso charmant und liebenswert sind wie die alten.

Die Grafik ist noch atemberaubender als im ersten Teil und die Animationen sind fl√ºssiger und detaillierter. Die Hintergr√ºnde sind immer noch wundersch√∂n und die Nekos sind s√º√üer als je zuvor. Der Soundtrack ist ebenfalls gro√üartig und f√§ngt perfekt die Stimmung des Spiels ein.

Das Gameplay ist √§hnlich wie im ersten Teil, aber es gibt neue Elemente wie das Training der Nekos und die M√∂glichkeit, sie zu kleiden und zu dekorieren. Es gibt auch mehrere Enden, je nach den Entscheidungen des Spielers.

Die Geschichte ist emotionaler und tiefgr√ºndiger als im ersten Teil und es gibt viele Momente, die den Spieler zum Lachen und zum Weinen bringen werden. Die Beziehungen zwischen den Charakteren sind komplexer und es gibt viele √úberraschungen und Wendungen in der Handlung.

Insgesamt ist Nekopara Vol.2 ein weiteres gro√üartiges Spiel f√ºr Fans der Serie. Es bietet eine Fortsetzung der Geschichte, die tiefgr√ºndiger und emotionaler ist als der erste Teil. author: {'steamid': '76561198175575166', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 52, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 52, 'last_played': 1515269688}
review:
Nekopara Vol.2 has emerged as a shining gem within the visual novel genre, effortlessly surpassing the lofty expectations set by its predecessor, Nekopara Vol.1. This captivating sequel has taken everything that made the original a masterpiece and elevated it to new heights. With its heartfelt storytelling, enchanting visuals, and an even more endearing cast of characters, Nekopara Vol.2 proves itself to be a worthy successor, solidifying its place as a true gem among visual novels.

Continuing the journey of the charming catgirls and their master, Kashou Minaduki, Nekopara Vol.2 delves even deeper into their relationships, their individual growth, and the bonds that tie them together. The narrative is beautifully woven, effortlessly blending moments of humor, heartfelt emotions, and captivating drama. As the story unfolds, players are drawn into a rich tapestry of love, friendship, and personal discovery that tugs at the heartstrings in the most enchanting way.

Once again, the visual presentation in Nekopara Vol.2 is nothing short of breathtaking. The character designs maintain the same level of meticulous detail as before, capturing the unique personalities of each catgirl with impeccable precision. The vibrant backgrounds and richly textured settings immerse players in a world that feels alive and inviting. Every frame is a visual treat, and the attention to detail is commendable, from the character animations to the small nuances that bring the world of Nekopara to life.

The sequel also shines in its character development, as each catgirl blossoms into a more fully realized and multi-dimensional character. Their growth is evident through the compelling dialogue and interactions, which expertly balance moments of lightheartedness and introspection. Nekopara Vol.2 further deepens the connections between the characters, allowing players to forge even stronger emotional bonds with them. The writers have succeeded in creating a cast that feels like a family, and their camaraderie is both heartwarming and genuinely moving.

Additionally, the soundtrack in Nekopara Vol.2 is a masterpiece in its own right. The music enhances the emotional impact of every scene, seamlessly blending with the narrative to create an immersive experience. From tender melodies that tug at the heartstrings to energetic tracks that accompany moments of excitement, the soundtrack captures the essence of the story, elevating the overall atmosphere and leaving a lasting impression on players.

Nekopara Vol.2 maintains the high standards set by its predecessor, while simultaneously pushing the boundaries and offering new surprises. It is a testament to the dedication and passion of the developers, who have once again crafted a visual novel that transcends the genre. The game immerses players in a world of unconditional love, personal growth, and heartwarming moments that will stay with them long after the final scene fades.

In conclusion, Nekopara Vol.2 is a triumphant continuation of the series, showcasing the evolution and maturation of both the characters and the storytelling. With its enchanting narrative, stunning visuals, and an unforgettable cast, it stands as a worthy successor to the masterpiece that was Nekopara Vol.1. This visual novel has cemented its place among the genre's finest offerings, demonstrating that the world of Nekopara is a captivating and delightful realm that continues to captivate and charm players with its irresistible allure.

review:
Nekopara Vol. 2 is an absolutely adorable and kawaii game that is sure to delight fans of the genre. The customization options in this game are particularly impressive, allowing players to adjust the bounciness of the characters to their liking, if you know what I mean. Whether you prefer a little jiggle or a lot of bounce, Nekopara Vol. 2 has got you covered!

But that's not all - this game is so charming and heartwarming that it will make you want to open up a cozy caf√© and adopt a cat (or two) of your own! The story and characters are just so sweet and endearing, it's impossible not to fall in love with them.

What really sets this game apart, however, is the sheer uwu factor. From the charming and playful dialogue to the delightful character designs, everything about Nekopara Vol. 2 is guaranteed to make you smile. Whether you're a longtime fan of the series or new to the world of cute and cuddly visual novels, this game is an absolute must-play.

Overall, I would highly recommend Nekopara Vol. 2 to anyone looking for a fun and lighthearted gaming experience. With its excellent customization options, charming characters, and overall kawaii aesthetic, this game is sure to be a hit with fans of all ages. So what are you waiting for? Pick up your copy of Nekopara Vol. 2 today and get ready to say uwu, uwu, uwu - and maybe even start planning your own cat caf√©!

author: {'steamid': '76561198802826571', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 55, 'playtime_forever': 792, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 792, 'last_played': 1680772741}
review:
After finally surviving seven chapters of Nekopara 2, I feel now is an appropriate time to review this dumpster fire. Before you buy the game; however, I must warn you the game has depictions of pee. Something the devs have not put up a disclaimer for. Now you know why my review is negative, or at least part of the reason why.

The story picks up after the original of course featuring a boring protagonist and his two neko frick addicts. The beginning is about as cliche and uninspiring as the entire story. During this setting, you will romance two catgirls with very little conflict in the story. Any conflict which does occur, is either resolved immediately or benign. During the beginning, you will also meet two supporting characters after an event the writers force to make one of the catgirls seem great. This particular event felt forced and uncharacteristic in addition to contributing nothing to the plot in any meaningful way. Throughout the story, you'll see the same recycled gimmick from the original with the exception of one of the two original catpanions helping you "romance" either of the new catgirls

The "plot" might be the most you'll get out of this game. You get Chocola and Vanilla raiding your bath for the forbidden eclair (cream filled pastry). After which I got scenes which overstayed their welcome with long clicking times where the two characters went into great detail about what was going on like a race coordinator relaying information going on in a NASCAR event. The main protagonist lacks the expression during these critical moment required to at least make the scenes entertaining and would probably be more fitting to be on the receiving end. Both of the newer catpanions talk about being inexperienced and asked for help during the act from their sisters. Not my thing, but I thought it was important enough to write down. Coconut was decent and the writers knew what the designers were thinking. Azuki... I wish they warned me about the water sports. That scene alone made me uncomfortable as a whole and the fact there was no warning on the store, reviews, or game made me genuinely upset and I think the consumer has a right to be informed of the details of the adult content present in the game.

Design-wise, the game has great art and animation. The music is great, but repetitive and lacks a broad selection. This alone isn't a deal breaker, but they've added only one new track since the first game. I'm honestly not sure if people buy this game out of sincerity or if it's a secret meme to pretend to like or dislike the game in a shallow manner.

I'm giving this an official rating of 35/100 with the majority of points being subtracted due to a huge turnoff present in the adult content. Due to this, I am not be able to recommend the game to anyone nor do I want to.

author: {'steamid': '76561198062247697', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 204, 'playtime_forever': 429, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 429, 'last_played': 1672348055}
review:
The second release of Nekopara, will it live up to the name of the Vol. 1, ruin the franchise, or drag the name over the hornyland mudfields? You can bet on option 3, in spite of my negative review.

The very mundane plot continues with Kashou and the 6 maid-catgirl from the Minaduki Family living/working together in his new bakery, the Neko Paradise. Once again: kinetic novel, no choices at all. This game focus on Azuki and Coconut, though Chocola and Vanilla still play a pivotal role in the story. Who am I kidding, nobody is pivotal here. Here the catgirls will talk about their insecurities and their sisterhood and a lot of wholesome stuff as well. From that perspective, Nekopara Vol. 2 is quite okay.

As opposed to Vol. 1, the heroines here talk and act more mature (Coconut also looks more mature; Azuki is supposed to be the oldest one, but still has a "loli" design). They are using the same engine, so the UI and everything else feels exactly like in Vol. 1. You can still keep the subtitles in English AND Japanese, if you're leaning Kanji!

EXCEPT THAT NOW YOU CAN PET THEM!!! *_*

Yoshi, Yoshi, calm down. 

Putting everything on a balance, there is still too much remains from Vol 1. here. Coconut's character is adorable, however.

Achievements are good and everything worked perfectly on Linux via Proton (thanks Valve!). My nekophile [spoiler]someone who loves catgirls[/spoiler] senses are begging me to thumb this up, but I will resist. Nope.

author: {'steamid': '76561198263769632', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 39, 'playtime_forever': 202, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 169, 'last_played': 1690443413}
review:
I expected the harem ending since vol 1, but it actually surprised me a little, in a positive way.
As expected, this vol focuses in adding Coconut and Azuki as catpanions, but i really liked how they treat poligamy and consent in this franchise. The MC actually worries about their catpanion's feelings and ask the previous partners before adding someone more to the love group, it's very nice and refreshing to see his caring attitude.

review: Auf jeden Fall eine extreme Verbesserung im Vergleich zum vorherigen Teil. Die Mimik Von den Charakteren passen jetzt viel besser zu den Situationen. Die Bewegungen und die allgemeinen Animationen sind viel Dynamischer. Die Story Parts waren viel besser geschrieben. Vor allem die Dramatischen Momente. Es gibt noch Luft nach oben, aber die waren echt gut. Wie die Charaktere gehandelt haben war auch viel glaubw√ºrdiger. Das Einzige was ich jetzt noch als Kritikpunkt hab, sind die H-Szenen. Nicht die Animationen. Daf√ºr aber die Struktur und wie diese geschrieben sind. Offensichtlich kann ich hier schlecht ins Detail gehen. Ich muss aber sagen, dass sich alle mit Ausnahme von Azuki alle gleich anf√ºhlten, das gleiche m√∂gen und gleich handeln. Das wird mir pers√∂nlich Langsam zu "Monoton". Aber sonst habe ich das Spiel sehr genossen.

review: I really love this series and nekopara vol 2 is really my favorite in regards to characters. I also love this story progression and showing the trend that occurs in all the other games of the series, They show the development of two of the characters or in this case the catgirls and by Nekopara vol 4 the Main character. I really love the character Azuki so to see her growth in the series is also a plus for me. As for vol 2 it does have also chocola and vanilla my favorite charcters in the series but as time goes on including vol 2 and onward there really no growth or future things with the catgirls like azuki or coconut. But  would still highly recommend playing all the games from begining to end and start with extra, zero and 1 before you start vol 2. But play the entire series and even if you don't this story is fun to play on your own highly recommend

review:
Well ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•!...
I Told Myself I Wouldn't Get Too Invested Into The Nekopara Collection And Yet Here I Am With Almost 10Hours Of Playtime, All Achievements Unlocked From The First Three Games And About To Buy The Next Chapter In The Nekopara Series...

What Can I Say Other Than I 100% Recommend Playing These Games...

Amazing Lore And Story And On Point Voice Acting Paired With Amazing Art Style And Ashetics...

Sure It Gets Lewd Towards The End Of The Game But The Story Outweighs The Lewdness...

I Recomended Not Playing This Game In Public Or Around People Who Would Find It Weird... Unless Your A Giga Chad Then Go Ahead, I Gave You Fair Warning...

Overall Would Recommend 10/10...

Connection terminated. I'm sorry to interrupt you, Elizabeth, if you still even remember that name, But I'm afraid you've been misinformed. You are not here to receive a gift, nor have you been called here by the individual you assume, although, you have indeed been called. You have all been called here, into a labyrinth of sounds and smells, misdirection and misfortune. A labyrinth with no exit, a maze with no prize. You don't even realize that you are trapped. Your lust for blood has driven you in endless circles, chasing the cries of children in some unseen chamber, always seeming so near, yet somehow out of reach, but you will never find them. None of you will. This is where your story ends.

And to you, my brave volunteer, who somehow found this job listing not intended for you, although there was a way out planned for you, I have a feeling that's not what you want. I have a feeling that you are right where you want to be. I am remaining as well. I am nearby. This place will not be remembered, and the memory of everything that started this can finally begin to fade away. As the agony of every tragedy should.

And to you monsters trapped in the corridors, be still and give up your spirits. They don't belong to you. For most of you, I believe there is peace and perhaps more waiting for you after the smoke clears. Although, for one of you, the darkest pit of Hell has opened to swallow you whole, so don't keep the devil waiting, old friend.

My daughter, if you can hear me, I knew you would return as well. It's in your nature to protect the innocent. I'm sorry that on that day, the day you were shut out and left to die, no one was there to lift you up into their arms the way you lifted others into yours, and then, what became of you. I should have known you wouldn't be content to disappear, not my daughter. I couldn't save you then, so let me save you now. It's time to rest - for you, and for those you have carried in your arms.

This ends for all of us.

End communication.

author: {'steamid': '76561198314735830', 'num_games_owned': 179, 'num_reviews': 16, 'playtime_forever': 21134, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 336, 'last_played': 1686735172}
review:
More Nekopara but this time the focus has shifted from Chocola and Vanilla to Coconut and Azuki. 
While this one is a bit longer than 1, I personally did not enjoy it as much however its still really good.

While the option to purchase another 18+ dlc may turn ppl away, I assume this would be another case like Nekopara vol. 1 where it is 100% optional. However, at least at the time of making this review, I have no evidence of what the story would be like without it as they haven't made a Nekopara vol. 2 movie and I have yet to play the game without it.

In the end tho if you liked 1 I would really recommend this game as its just more Nekopara and the reason I liked 1 more is just because I like the Chocola and Vanilla pair better than the Azuki and Coconut pair. Not to mention that the 3rd Nekopara game is really good as well and I would not recommend skipping 2 just so you can play 3 sooner.

author: {'steamid': '76561198240876340', 'num_games_owned': 131, 'num_reviews': 11, 'playtime_forever': 233, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 233, 'last_played': 1598209829}
review: I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single farther to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just, watching YouTube. So I decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. loaded into the game, made my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you were supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. loved it as it was the best time had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

author: {'steamid': '76561198996221369', 'num_games_owned': 113, 'num_reviews': 17, 'playtime_forever': 664, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 604, 'last_played': 1668564294}
review:
[b]November 15th, 2021[/b]

"What if I got one of the Nekopara games, like, say, volume 2, just to get thousands of hours on it? I think that'd be pretty funny. I'm not just gonna let 10 bucks go to waste either. I'm gonna read this shit, and see what the hell this is all about before I just leave this idle for weeks at a time."

This is an approximation of what I said on Discord to my friends (The golfing friends I golfed with in Golf with your Friends, for clarification) roughly 30 minutes before downloading this game (which is a bit of a stretch, but it is on Steam, Switch, and PS4). Little did I know, that at that time, I would be starting my journey through the uncanny, yet engaging, Nekopara franchise. I arbitrarily chose Volume 2 as my entry point into the series, as I was not anticipating to read beyond this entry, fully expecting myself to laugh off the seeming evidence of human degeneracy I saw in front of me. This may or may not have been a bad decision on my part, starting where I did.

But before I dive into this review I will impart a few words, a synopsis of sorts, on my views of this game:

[i]There is no work of fiction that is more conflicting to me than Nekopara.[/i]

This is my way of saying that I can't make up my mind whether this game is good or bad. There are aspects within the games that are terrible, sure (*cough* Shigure *cough*), but these parts add to the experience, in a funny sort of way. The presentation of the catgirls, within the universe created, are too weird to like, and yet at the same time I found it not weird enough to hate. Each of the catgirls have their own personalities, and aside from some catlike tendencies mostly find themselves falling into tropes you'd typically see in most anime. I quickly found out that these catgirls aren't even the strangest part of this series, and the questions I asked myself during and after my read-through of Volume 2 had nothing to do with any of the dialogue that made me cringe. 

My experience with Nekopara: Volume 2 began on the title screen. I was under the impression at the time that Nekopara was a dating sim, and not a visual novel, as I was going into this game possessing no outside knowledge of substance. The characters in the forefront this time around are Coconut, a clumsy but hardworking catgirl who gets in her own way at times, and Azuki, the eldest, yet shortest, catgirl of the Minaduki household, who worries for her sisters, despite her constant bickering with Coconut. The story revolves around bringing them closer together, as one might infer after reading through the first chapter.

Clicking the left mouse button or scrolling down on the scroll wheel advances the dialogue, which is what you will be doing for 98% of the game. The game has quick-save and quick-load functions, numerous save files for you to instantly jump around your favorite scenes (ya know, [i]THOSE[/i] ones), a fast forward function, and scrolling up on the mouse wheel will show you previous lines. The game, by design, is meant to be played with one hand, probably for simplicity's sake but what do I know? The game's interactivity comes in the form of the "petting" function, which has been a mainstay of the series since Volume 0. From within this function, you can pet any of the characters that show up on the screen (i.e. Shigure, Milk, and the 6 catgirl sisters). In addition to this, pressing the 'P' key in "pet" mode will cause the character(s) on screen to hop up, and if you noticed the "Chest Bounciness" slider in the options menu, that will also reflect what happens when 'P' is pressed. There are 3 language options as well: English, Chinese, and Japanese, but know that the voice acting is only Japanese. If you know all of this, then congratulations! You can now 100% this game by exploring these features as much as you can.

The main plot of the game is not offensively bad like I was expecting it to be, but don't hold your breath expecting the writing to win any awards, either. Coconut is fine enough as a character, but her habit of saying "onee-chan, this" and "onii-chan" annoyed me more than it should have. Azuki's whole arc kinda felt shoehorned into the story despite being one of the main characters in it, but she had 1 or 2 funny lines here and there, so her presence wasn't insufferable.

However, what really got me hooked on this series were the various happenings that were present outside the main storyline, funnily enough, a lot of which distracted me from the main plot and had me asking a lot of questions.

For instance, the whole way that society in Nekopara is set up is reminiscent of a sort of slave state that no one questions. Catgirls, despite appearing almost the same as humans, talking (almost) like humans, and adapting to living in a human society where they can assist humans with human tasks, as the Minaduki catgirls do at La Soleil (the game's main setting), the system is still set up as an owner-pet system where catgirls are legally not allowed to live on their own without an owner, and are not even allowed to go out unsupervised without proper documentation. This is a cutesy, anime-like slave state wrapped up in a neat bow whose status quo is rarely challenged throughout the series.

What the fuck?

Kashou is essentially employing his family pets in what looks like full-time work, and there is no evidence that he is even paying them minimum wage (or if there is a minimum wage in the first place). At the same time the catgirls are completely content with their situation, treating the tests to obtain documents that grant them a mere sliver of independence as we would a school exam or job interview, as a necessary evil, but not inherently wrong. One of my friends was scouting the wiki for me while I was reading Volume 2, and we learned that catgirls caught without proper identification are taken into police custody, like animal control taking a stray pet to the pound. The identification (known as "bells" in-universe) also serve as tracking devices, so don't even think about running away because the law will track you down. All of this would be seriously messed up in our world, but it is hardly an afterthought in theirs, and that is what fascinated me more than anything in this game.

There is also the matter of how aging works in this universe. Catgirls, as my friend learned on the wiki shortly after I started reading Volume 2, have lifespans similar to common housecats (around 12 years), and 1 month in their time is about 2 years for a human. Before knowing this, I knew that this game had NSFW scenes in it (which contribute very little to the plot so they will mostly be ignored here), so I was hoping for dear life that the characters were of legal age, and some of them (Vanilla) were not making the answer obvious at all. After learning that the youngest catgirls in the game were 9 months old, and the oldest were 3 years of age, my initial reaction was, yet again, "What the fuck?". The ambiguity of "catgirl maturity" in this universe jumps through hoops and walks through broken glass where simpler rules can be established, so why do all of this in the first place? 

All of the side stuff that happened outside the main plot had me asking so many questions: "Who the hell are Maple and Cinnamon" "What is up with all the biology lessons from Vanilla and why do they matter?" "What's up with the slave society and the weird age rules?"

I could have known this ahead of time had I started with Volume 1, and thus avoided what came afterward. But I wanted answers, dammit, and I was prepared to dive headfirst into Volume 3 looking for them, despite the cringey dialogue and the generic story.

I only knew one thing at the end of Nekopara: Volume 2; that this wasn't a joke anymore.

tl;dr: nya nya catgirl game 2 leaves me too many questions. further examination required. 5/10

author: {'steamid': '76561198210239579', 'num_games_owned': 349, 'num_reviews': 87, 'playtime_forever': 12, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 12, 'last_played': 1640669199}
review:
I have never in my life been so thoroughly bored playing a game. Even titles like Crackhead, which I consider a complete waste of time and money, provided more entertainment than this. Visual novel games, such as the one in question, often run the risk of being inherently dull due to their heavy reliance on reading comics. However, many manage to inject excitement through mini-games or meaningful choices, which is sorely lacking here.

Beyond its monotonous gameplay, this game manages to make me uncomfortably ill at ease. It's difficult to recommend it, as it appears to cater exclusively to those with a particular penchant. While I may jokingly refer to myself as one for indulging in adult-oriented games, I cannot fathom aligning myself with individuals who genuinely derive pleasure from this specific title.

For those seeking entertainment, I would suggest turning to the anime adaptation instead. It offers a relatively enjoyable experience, free from the drawbacks and discomfort found within the game. However, I strongly caution against subjecting oneself to the tediousness and unease that accompany playing this title.

author: {'steamid': '76561198821123961', 'num_games_owned': 149, 'num_reviews': 27, 'playtime_forever': 333, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 329, 'last_played': 1666999590}
review:
After really enjoying the first Nekopara i decided to buy the second one.
A solid sequel to a great game. This one kinda flecthes out some of the characters a bit more, but mainly focus on Azuki and Coconut. Laying the games out like this where it starts off with Chocola and Vanilla, then Azuki and Coconut, and then Cinnamon and Maple, is a good way to go about it IMO. You don't get overflown with information about each character and their backstorys.
This one was deffinetly more touching than the first one but overall a more fun and relaxed game.

review:
Nekopara 2. The family love is strong no matter where can't break it.

As for nekopara all knows from previous nekopara focused on Chocola and Vanilla routes, this one focus for Azuki and Coconut routes. It's heavily focus on Azuki and Coconut relationship since they always conflicted as an older and younger sister. 

As much I judge the lewd of the game, it's mediocre and cute too. No yuri scene but they have seperate ways to handle their relationship with mc at the end. They are *balance* considered the small and big size ( Õ°¬∞ Õú ñ Õ°¬∞).

For my own review, great eroge and love to see the cat fight often ( Õ°¬∞ Õú ñ Õ°¬∞). 8/10 Azuki is a real tsundere.

author: {'steamid': '76561198095022965', 'num_games_owned': 403, 'num_reviews': 91, 'playtime_forever': 989, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 989, 'last_played': 1635032745}
review: You know what time it is! Its been over a year after I finally finished Vol. 1. Got my Chocola and Vanilla figures recently (my first ever figures btw), which finally made me pick up the slack yet again, made me hyped. I've always been very slow with visual novels, but I'm loving Nekopara more and more, and I can feel a bit of a binge incoming. Obviously I won't repeat the points in my Vol. 1 review, as its overall greatness is already embedded into it, but I will tell you how they keep nailing it! For some reason, the story this time around was very unexpected to me, gonna keep it quite spoiler free, so how I'm gonna say it is that you get strong presumptions of rest of the catgirl's personalities from Vol. 1, so I'm very happy at how surprisingly the story continues and how invested I became at getting to know the other girls better. I'm not sure why, but I definitely enjoyed Vol. 2 even more than its predecessor and that makes me excited for and love Nekopara even more. Also, for the first time in at least a while, I'm really enjoying the pattern in the story that you'll notice, why? Cause I love the mischievousness of both Chocola and Vanilla! That's all you're getting on that! >:) While undeniably Vol. 2 makes you fall for Chocola and Vanilla even more, adore them even further, you'll as hopelessly as Kashou, start liking the "other" catgirls as well, they're all so adorable and that's what makes Nekopara a catgirl paradise! Yup, as always, Nekopara never disappoints with its overload of cuteness and I just can't help but to gobble it all up, the more I play. However, I obviously won't forget to talk about how the H-scenes this time around are even better, cuter and lewder and not only the scenes, but Chocola and Vanilla as well and I love it! The more cuteness and lewdness, the better, it's the best life can give, which is why I'm addicted to it and why I love Chocola and Vanilla so. I'm slowly becoming the Nekopara connoisseur that I had no escape from ever since launching Vol. 1 back in 2015, so I am with no doubt looking forward to more!

author: {'steamid': '76561198341144219', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 17, 'playtime_forever': 1891, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1891, 'last_played': 1610170992}
review: Liked it but wasn't all that interesting. The only thing that really stood out to me in this vol. was the feud between Azuki and Coconut. After that gets resolved nothing else super interesting happens. The main redeeming factor is that the feud between the two catgirls takes a looooong time to resolve. review:
Okay, Coconuts is my personal favourite catgirl in this series. Fight me. Her only flaw is her EXTREMELY fragile self-esteem.. caused by growing up around the haughty attitude of Azuki that instilled Coconut's severe inferiority complex.

Did you know that if you grow up listening to people calling you stupid, idiot or other similar derogatory name-calling, you will REALLY become THAT? Due to that, I can't bring myself to even try to understand characters like Azuki, much less even liking her. It might be cute if she behaves that way sometimes, but this game's case, behaving THAT way ALL THE TIME will not win any favors from me since I have a reflective personality when it comes to interacting with people.

Vol 2... do I even need to rate this since it's basically an expansion to the same visually beautiful game but with different central characters?

review:
Una obra maestra contempor√°nea. El segundo cap√≠tulo de la saga "Nekopara: Cats paradise" nos permite adentrarnos en las miembros de la familia Shigure que solo pudimos ver a la r√°pida en la primera entrega. Con un desarrollo de personajes incre√≠ble disfrutamos de una cr√≠tica social al r√©gimen capitalista desde una perspectiva anarco-primitiva, con algunos retoques que recuerdan a los ideales Marxistas. Todo esto mientras nos adentramos en el mundo obseso de la poligamia y el romance interespecies, como muestra del resultado del desligue a la moral actual de nuestra sociedad y un claro resalte hacia la subjetividad de esta misma. Nos devuelve a nuestras ra√≠ces destacando en nosotros mismos los deseos m√°s oscuros y enso√±aciones m√°s morbosas, oblig√°ndonos a sentirnos asqueados, pero a su vez, intrigados por consumirnos m√°s en la oscuridad del placer morboso. Una obra que a qui√©n la prueba genera disfrute y a qui√©n la analiza remordimientos fatales que act√∫an como un pu√±al al coraz√≥n y a la √©tica, volc√°ndonos en una vor√°gine de odio hacia nosotros mismos y hacia la humanidad como tal.

review:
Nekopara Volume 2 is the sequel to the highly praised Nekopara Volume 1, and is bigger and better in every way.
This entry follows Azuki and Coconut, catgirls who are very sister-like and very caring of their younger relatives and worried that they're not good at anything, respectively.
This game features the same raw, vigorous sex that you bought it for, yet contains some very emotional and wholesome moments that are sure to kill your boner(for the dudes) and whatever the equivalent is for the lovely ladies out there(cheers to you all).
I highly recommend that you play this if you have any interest in catgirl sex.

author: {'steamid': '76561198278467883', 'num_games_owned': 149, 'num_reviews': 8, 'playtime_forever': 461709, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 243683, 'last_played': 1634384852}
review:
This game saved my life.

I am 27.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiraling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•ing minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

Thank you

author: {'steamid': '76561197997678124', 'num_games_owned': 1630, 'num_reviews': 443, 'playtime_forever': 67, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 67, 'last_played': 1619287067}
review:
My adoration for Nekos will be the end of me some day. :P

Fun story, adorable characters that you can pet/bounce, and a really exciting video/gallery area where you can re-watch all the sex scenes. 

My only problem is the awful noise that sex makes. It sounds like someone is plunging a toilet. I had to shut off sound effects to be able to get through the scenes with a straight face. They probably would have done better if they recorded the sound of punching a bowl of cooked macaroni, but that's just my opinion.

As much as I love the Nekopara games, I do find them to be overpriced. So I will almost always recommend purchasing them on sale. <3

Game on, friends. :)

author: {'steamid': '76561198869605383', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 13, 'playtime_forever': 454, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 454, 'last_played': 1619199463}
review:
I thought I would try this game since Coconut is in it. However, it was an utter disappointment like the first game.

A lot of issues come from:

*audio and video sync doesn't match; the opening and ending movies are too slow, so the songs end before the opening and endings movies end up taking another minute or two to finish playing.

*Kashou is a boring MC who gets way too influenced into having sexual relationships with his family's cats

*No interesting story, seeing as Chocola and Vanilla play the roles of [spoiler] "sexual helpers" and tease Coconut and Azuki too much during the sex scenes, which in turn gives Kashou too much enjoyment; this is really disgusting to see how there is no privacy in just having Kashou and Coconut, or Kashou and Azuki moments. [/spoiler]

I stopped caring about any of the characters, except for Shigure, who has funny moments and has a more professional personality, in spite of her brother complex. Shigure is a better caretaker and sister compared to most visual novels.

review: A continuation of a truly perfect game is often times hard to master. However, that is not the case in this wonderful franchise as Nekopara Vol. 2 exceeds all expectations. This game is a cinematic masterpiece with awe-inspiring plot that rivals the work of Shakespeare himself. I don't know what the following games will have in store, but I can say it is evident beyond a reasonable doubt that this franchise will definitely be in the history books as one of the best.

review: Look, I‚Äôve already reviewed the first visual novel. The previous two games were a great setup for Nekopara 2 the cat girls and cafe definitely grow alongside the story. If cat girls did exist (and god do I wish they did) this would be the perfect guide to talk to them. Now to get to what matters, I can‚Äôt stress enough how much this VN makes me hard. It‚Äôs like I took six Viagras. The drawings are border line artwork, you could probably put some of these screenshots in the Louvre [and I have quite a few screenshots :wink:  ]. I definitely play it for the plot though, I love how the characters seem realistic, I'm going to start using this game as a guide to talk to girls. Maybe I'll even make a few girlfriends. The characters all look huggable and squeezable. I might even buy a body pillow of one of the characters.

review:
As the second game Vol. 2 is more polished and clean compared to the first game. With its voice-acting and e-mote system it is one of the most immersive game in the visual novel space.

The story is more focused in Coconut and Azuki but it does not forget the other characters in the story. The story is very light hearted for the most part with having some emotional moments. 18+ patch is also top-notch and worth buying 100% since it also has character development in it.

In the franchise Vol. 2 is the most forgettable of the games as it does not add too much to the story in the long run compared to the other volumes. But still it is worth buying and playing through.

9/10 A masterpiece that only loses to other games in the franchise.

author: {'steamid': '76561198271242786', 'num_games_owned': 361, 'num_reviews': 20, 'playtime_forever': 123, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 123, 'last_played': 1609986932}
review:
If you've played the first installment and liked it, this one will feel right at Home. Apart from introducing you more to Coconut and Azuki, especially in the R-18 scenes (like with the first one, you'll need a seperate DLC for those), Vol. 2 really lives up to the quality of the first game. That being said, this game does not have that much improvements overall (which isn't necessarily bad - why change a almost perfect formula?), except from the new "petting" mechanic that allows you to interact with the girls in a more direct way, basically you drag your mouse across them and they react accordingly. Sadly this mechanic feels more like a gimmick than anything else, because its pretty much the same for all the girls and after doing it once, you have basically seen it all.

All in all this part definitely lives up too the expectations of Vol.1 and continues the Story right where it left of. If you haven't played the first one, there really is no reason to start with Vol.2 whatsoever, because you aren't missing out on anything.

author: {'steamid': '76561198121644456', 'num_games_owned': 283, 'num_reviews': 75, 'playtime_forever': 433, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 289, 'last_played': 1673883494}
review:
Do yourself a favour and play Volume 2 of Nekopara.

The GUI and music remains mostly the same as the previous two instalments, which is nice because if it ain't broke, you've no reason to fix it.

The music in this game is seriously well done. Visual novel music has always managed to impress me, but the music in this series has seriously caught me off guard. It's so exceptionally designed that it's just so pleasing to listen to. Even if I don't play the games that much (because it's story driven, there's not a whole lot of replayability), I still find myself listening to the OST every once and a while. If a game's OST has left that much of an impact on you, you've definitely done something right.

The visuals for this game are stunning. The character sprites, the animations, the backgrounds, the CGs, all of it. They all look astounding in terms of quality. I understand that NekoWorks is more than one person and so the quality of these games will definitely be higher than that of an indie dev. Going off of that, it would be unfair to draw any comparisons, but I have to admit that when I look upon this game's artwork, it all just fits together so well. With other visual novels, I sometimes find that the artwork doesn't hit me the same way as it does in this. In this game, the artwork truly shines.

The voice acting is wonderful. You can tell that each of the VAs truly went all out with their roles, whether that was capturing the whole dynamic of sisters having an argument with each other, to the more sensual and intimate exchanges throughout, or completely losing their cool. It's so diverse and the VAs did a really good job. It truly helps bring the characters to life.

Visual novels are difficult to get right, because you're telling a story, but also supplying the players with visuals, audio and everything else. If you don't balance it correctly, then your visual novel can very easily flop. With this game, and then other Volumes in the series, it all just feels incredibly balanced.

At face value, it's a silly visual novel about a man and his catgirls making love or what have you, but this was a really pleasant game for various reasons.

Volume 1 focuses primarily on Chocola and Vanilla and their interactions with Kashou (the protagonist) with guest introductions from the other catgirls and characters, whereas Volume 2 focuses primarily on Azuki and Coconut and their interactions with Kashou, with Chocola and Vanilla playing supporting roles and the others playing guest introductions.

We get to learn more about Azuki and Coconut, and honestly...they're both written to be really relatable / understandable on a level that goes more in-depth. Like I said, it might seem like a silly game about catgirls and falling in love with them, but when you've got me getting this emotionally attached to their characters and they way they're written...you've seriously done something really incredible, and I'm not just saying that because I'm weak for catgirls, either.

All in all, Nekopara Volume 2 gets an 11/10 from me, I genuinely think that this game is a masterpiece, there is a reason why it has an overwhelmingly positive response. Obviously, the whole theme of it is not for everyone, but if you are even just a little bit intrigued, I implore you to give it a go. You may be pleasantly surprised by what you encounter. Though, please make sure you play them in order, it'll be a lot better that way.

Nya~

author: {'steamid': '76561198095732542', 'num_games_owned': 220, 'num_reviews': 71, 'playtime_forever': 789, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 789, 'last_played': 1611629879}
review:
I've come to really enjoy these games, with no shame. The story gets more rich with each installment in the series. The character's different personalities really shines through, and you can really find your favorite ones. It's also a little longer, and you get more 'content' with different Nekos.

The deep narrative honestly keeps me coming back to these. It's simple, yet effective. You just can't help but enjoy this visual novel. 7/10!

author: {'steamid': '76561198272443989', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 60, 'playtime_forever': 295, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 290, 'last_played': 1649128003}
review: Despite the lack of cat girl h3ntai, both Coconut and Azuki are given great development that fleshes them out as characters ranging from Coconut's sister complex to Azuki's responsibility as the eldest sibling. There were times I nearly cried and felt sorry for them. Coconut and Azuki's struggles are realistic circumstances that others face daily. For me personally, it was an emotional roller coaster got me invested in their relationship. Seeing what would happen next, had me at the edge of my seat. The characters maybe 2D, but they feel 3D (in the figurative sense) thanks to this game's excellent story writing. If this game did not remove the h3ntai scenes, I would have considered this to be a masterpiece, but it's still a great game in terms of story

review:
I often think that if I had lost my virginity in high school I wouldn't have ever played this game.
Well here I am in college writing a review for porn. And before you say "it no hv pron.!" I would like you to know that this game is indeed porn. Well, at least now it is, seeing how I aggressively pulled out my sweat scented debit card from my back pocket, in what can only be described as a fit of pure ecstasy to buy the DLC. During the event it never once occurred to me that I could simply look up the missing scenes on PornHub, and save myself a few bucks and a bit of dignity. But no, the folks over at Patisserie La Soleil needed my dollars more than me. It was a small price to pay to hear the sound of cat girls in heat pour from my headphones at 3 in the morning. Watching in awe as they get filled up by an oddly shaped object made entirely of pixels. All in all, I regret nothing.

10/10 IGN

author: {'steamid': '76561198250654632', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 498, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 498, 'last_played': 1596169539}
review:
So I finished Vol 1 the other day and thought it really couldn't get any better. Holy crap was I wrong! This is outstanding and a great add-on to the story. My only issue with this series is why they did not add this in depth story telling to the Anime? What are they thinking?

As the story goes on you start hoping for Coconut. Will she give up the act? Will she learn about the love from the older sister? Does she understand her own feelings?
What about Azuki? Why does she push herself? Is being the oldest really what drives that attitude?
Not going to lie about it, watching Azuki grow and come into her own feelings brought a few tears to my eyes. The relationship between sisters shown in this story is outstanding. 

Now for the DLC - Just buy it. I understand it is an adult patch and some people might not be into that. However, it adds to the story. It shows the internal feelings of the characters. It is really nice to see the feelings develop. Over all while yes it is pervy... It really does add to the game. I am glad I bought them. 

Over all great story. Developers if you ever read this, fix the anime! While a good "feel good" anime you need to add these stories. The character development in this visual novel was outstanding. Don't sell yourselves short.

author: {'steamid': '76561198799326143', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 13, 'playtime_forever': 59626, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 2457, 'last_played': 1697175989}
review: I haven't left my room in about two days. I am absolutely mezmorised at how perfect this game is. From its great graphics, the extremely well detailed and in deph plot, to the one handed support (with the other hand I was watching tutorials on how to get all the 37 endings, ecspecially the one where-- oops! don't want to spoil! Anyways, back to the review. The cat girls in this game are outstanding to be around. I like to imagine that I am the main character and that everything is real! (Call me selfish idc) But the girls are so attractive, each in their own way. From their outstanding personalities, to their outstanding beauty, any man who isn't an idiot would love to feel the nice, warm, welcoming embrace from ANY of these girls. Now, the plot. As of today, I am still on chapter 2. I know its been a day, but I really want to soak up ALL that this game has to offer. But so far, I am having a blast. Next, the music. GOD the music is just pure bliss as it hits your ears! Those tunes get stuck in your head so quickly, but you will want them to stay there. Anyways, I am gonna take a five minute break to go and get something to eat, and break up with my girlfriend because who needs real girls when you have Nekopara Vol 2? Edit: I just finished chapter 3. After a day of staring at my computer screen, and the eyes of these beautiful nekos, I think I might have a heart attack. All the scenes were just outstanding! I am gonna start 3/4's of my paycheck to whoever developed this wonderful game. Anyways, I haven't been outside in a day and I need to get the mail. Edit 2: I really enjoy this game. I'm still trying to get ending 24 because it's really difficult. Hopefully I can get there soon!

review:
An amazing game series and it doesn't disappoint even now, and this one is my favourite out of all of them. Coconut is gorgeous true, but you find out a lot more about her and really feel bad for her since she puts so much pressure on herself. And Azuki just as much being both cute and stubborn, but you find through her story she really wants to be loved just like the others. But she is the typical tsundere so yea. Both of these girls are my 2 most favourite characters and loves seeing their characters develop more.
Again another great game in the series and one I highly recommend.

review: Over the past 1000 hours that I have spent in the past couple months playing this game, I have come to realize that that is an IMPECCABLE game. It is full of adorable nekos all around with an interesting and twisting story line. I would highly recommend this to anyone looking for a good story game! The 18+ content on the side has also shown me that I am a complete degenerate and I am proud of that. I take full responsibility of watching big neko titty for 1k+ hours and beyond. I have no shame at all in what I have done and beat it to for the past few months. This was a perfect use of my time. In conclusion, Coconut and Azuki are the best in the series and I hope to see even more in vol.4 and more neko titty. :) (this is satirical lol)

author: {'steamid': '76561198085723952', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 149, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 19, 'last_played': 1593589119}
review:
So you know that feeling when once for a while you want to chill and play some casual video games, right? And you're tired of competitive matchmaking and toxic communities. Meanwhile, your friends have a high skill level, and they mob together with no spare space in the lobby for you? Say no more!

Here is a solution: play Nekopara. No skill requests. No communication. No connection to the real-world problems. Only cute anime catgirls in maid uniform. What's that? Are you caring about your reputation? Are you afraid that any of your friends will eventually think that you're miserable and pathetic weeb? No need to worry. Just think of it as a postmodern artistic performance with a high degree of self-irony. 

Diving balls-deep into the world of catgirls won't help you fight your depression. It won't help you to get a life either. Nevertheless, it's quite an enjoyable way of wasting your time, especially when you have no other options left. 

"Maybe self-improvement is not the answer... Maybe self-destruction is the answer."
P.S. "Self-improvement is masturbation" (c) Tyler Durden

review: So what makes this volume better than the last? Here is my honest opinions on this volume and what makes this one better than the first. First off there are new features in this volume that do not appear in the first. The best mechanic by far is the petting mechanic. The reason this mechanic stands out is because one, it wasn't in the first one, and there was clearly attention to detail when programming it. Based on the body parts you touch the neko girls make a different animation. Another addition to this volume, was the higher quality models. I noticed when comparing the two, there was a clear difference in the quality of both the models. Besides mechanics and new features, Neko Works clearly didn't slack on the story. This time around the story was extremely refreshing and (in my opinion) was better than volume one's story. None the less, it is an extremely good Nekopara game and I am glad I read and played it.

review: It does well for what it is, a silly visual novel about catgirls. The background visuals are pretty good and the animations are well done, there's even a slider for more 'chest bounciness'. On the spoiled side, the novel literally has an 'Auto-Play' button, and a game that plays by itself can't really be called a "game". If you're looking to bust a nut, the H-scenes are pretty light with almost no fancy kinks, mostly vanilla intercourses (no pun intended). Nekopara isn't essentially bad or anything, I'm just saying it's one of those games you would get the same experience by watching a No Commentary gameplay on YouTube. There are no choices, different paths or endings, you play in a straight line and that's about it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198347791795', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 478, 'playtime_forever': 352, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 237, 'last_played': 1590775511}
review:
Nekopara Vol 2 continues from where Nekopara Vol 1 left off in the last chapter of Nekopara Vol 1 we saw that the entire Minaduki family start working in the "La Soleil" or "Neko Paradise" pastry we got all lovey-dovey with Chocola and Vanilla in Vol 1 and now we see the story of Azuki and Coconut the families oldest member that has a cutting board for boobs Azuki and the families youngest (older than Vanilla and Chocola but younger than everyone else) member Coconut our character gets all lovey-dovey with them too unlike the other games this one is not too short nor too long the others always felt too long this one was just right its just like all the other games pretty cute and id say that the way the characters move the way they act the stuff they say id say its much better than the other games more visuals,more interesting conversations its pretty good in general

+cute
+the game sounds looks and plays fine (you just press left mouse button to continue the story and read stuff thats the "playing" youll do its a visual novel for fucks sake what did you expect ?)
+the game doesnt feel too short nor too long
+the stuff the characters say,the way they move,the scenes it all looks better it sounds better and there is more variety between facial expressions this time

+/- the 18+ DLC is pretty nice but you dont gain anything from having it and you dont lose anything from not having it its there for "research purposes" only id doubt  you would miss much of the story cuz you didnt have the 18+ DLC feel free to use that as an excuse tho if a friend asks why you have it just say "i thought id miss parts of the story without it" everyone will know that you are lying but hey its (probably) better than saying "i wanted to see boobs" actually fuck it be honest instead :D everyone knows why you have it already so...no point in trying to hide

the game is really good it was a much more enjoyable experience than the other Nekopara games there is more variety,more scenes and all of them look and sound better too and an 18+ DLC whats there to not like ? oh and you can pet the characters too (there is an achivement for petting all of them)i dont think the older games had that at least Vol 1 definetly didnt and you can press "P" on keyboard for...uhhh...an interesting little move lets leave it at that the game is cute its good if you are into the Nekopara series then buy this game too its pretty nice

author: {'steamid': '76561198804074552', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 44, 'playtime_forever': 159, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 124, 'last_played': 1603000792}
review: I went into this game not expecting to be fulfilled like volume 1 did... boy was I wrong. Let me start this with, the animation is so much better and the petting feature was also put in, so that helped. The story doesn't revolve around Chocola and Vanilla, I originally thought this was going to hurt the story... yet again I was wrong. Coconut and Azuki are such lovable cute characters at the core and this game really drags you in, you truly feel sad for Coconut when she is depressed. You feel like you yourself are there, something which volume 1 didn't do as well as this one. There is some development with Milk (the takoyaki stand catgirl), which in turn helps with Coconuts development. The characters truly grow throughout the story, and you get to witness it, which is beautiful. Overall I give this game a well deserved 9.6/10 (not to be IGN). Get this game if you enjoy a beautifully told Japanese story about female creatures with feline features!

author: {'steamid': '76561198045654838', 'num_games_owned': 237, 'num_reviews': 68, 'playtime_forever': 1155, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1153, 'last_played': 1672713978}
review:
[h2]NekoPara 2[/h2]
[i]You can never have enough Catgirls![/i]

[h3]Preclaimer[/h3]
- This is an Adult Visual Novel, designed to be R18, which is why I consider the R18 content part of the whole and will include it in this review. If for whatever reason you are not interested in this content or aren't legally allowed to play it, you should just skip this review.
- Since many Visual Novels are similar in a bunch of ways, I'm gonna review this one on a few common aspects, heavily referencing previous NekoPara titles.

[hr]
[h3]Chronology[/h3]
The order I personally recommend the games to be played in, though 1‚Üí2‚Üí3‚Üí4 should be obvious. The rest is optional.
[list][*][url=https://steamcommunity.com/id/0256667/recommended/333600/]NekoPara Vol.1[/url]
[*][i]NekoPara Vol.0 (1h long SoL FanDisc)[/i]
[*]NekoPara Vol.2 ‚Üê
[*]NekoPara Vol.3
[*][i]NekoPara Extra (2h long SoL bonus from the catgirls childhood)[/i]
[*]NekoPara Vol.4[/list]

[hr]
[url]https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1860653051[/url]

[hr]
[h3]Graphical & Technical Quality[/h3]
As to be expected from a successor of the NekoPara Franchise, Vol.2 steps up the game from it's predecessor noteably.
The game is still fully Live2D animated with visibly more and better animations. Other than that, it stayed mostly the same as Vol.1, giving you a solid VN with the usual basic features to enjoy.
80 saveslots, individually describable, quick saving and loading, auto and skip mode with behaviour customization, hidden advanced settings for more details and all together with smooth performance.

Vol.2 throws in another gimmick to play around with, which is the headpatting "minigame", allowing you to stop in any scene with characters onscreen and pat them, getting different reactions for different areas. *hint hint*

Alongside that, sadly Vol.2 seems to step up the game with more textual errors too, is still 720p and still having the idle lip sync bug when skipping animations too fast.

[hr]
[url]https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1860653091[/url]

[hr]
[h3]Content & Runtime[/h3]
What can you expect from NekoPara Vol.2?
Just like with Vol.1, Vol.2 mostly has an overly cute, very lighthearted romance story with the usual amount of comedy, though this time around there is actually a more noteable amount of actual deep(er) story and character development, revolving around the archetypes of the two heroines in focus.

The gallery enables you to re-enjoy the 30 CGs, 7 SD artworks and all OSTs, which are all from Vol.1 (minus OP/ED) plus 2 new ones and a fresh opening and ending song. Naturally you can enjoy said movies and all "scenes" too, all as longs as you saw them in the game first.

The game again is completely linear without any sort of player decisions, hence capping at around 10h of content (not rush-skipping) again.

[hr]
[h3]The R18 Content[/h3]
It is again mostly the same as Vol.1
There are 3 (GIF loop-ish) animated H-scenes with accompanying sound effects.
The depiction of bodily fluids, inhuman stamina of the actors and overall intensity of those scenes is still as unreal as the existence of catgirls (sadface), though this time around our good ol' friend the peeing fetish makes its grand debut.

[b]Mosaic censorship on the 'good' bits is still in place[/b], as is that weird safety measure when trying to share adult content from within Steam.

[hr]
[url]https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1860653179[/url]

[hr]
[h3]Conclusion[/h3]
Is this game worth it?
Well, obviously, if you enjoyed NekoPara Vol.1 then hell yes it's worth it. Though your best bet is buying the bundle in the next sale, so you should have this part already anyways.
If you're really planning on skipping Vol.1 and getting this here first, you aren't missing out on anything essential. Yes, NekoPara is (compared to multi route VNs) pretty expensive, though as long as you like Nekos and enjoy a cute Slice of Life harem romance story, it's worth it. The next sale is always around the corner anyway, just put it on your wishlist and wait.

review:
This takes less then 3 hours to fully read. No choices or alternate endings. The art, animation, and voice acting are all very good. The focus this time is on Azuki and Coconut being added to the harem. Lots of semen will be spilled by the end of this. There are a couple new fetishes added this time. 

Coconut is best girl. But Azuki was surprisingly very likable. I found Vol. 2 better then the first and look forward to banging the next two girls.

review:
The game took me by surprise when I first played it tbh.

The second volume of [b]NEKOPARA[/b] is an adult visual novel (well most of the game series actually). Essentially, the point of the game is to own [i]‚ÄúCatgirls‚Äù[/i] and treat them like pets (or something like that). The player has no influence on how the story pans out but it seems as if everybody loves the journey the game offers. 

I can't even review the game as plain and simple like [i]‚ÄúCome on guys why are you reading the reviews? Buy the game already! It's Nekopara! Neko's!! All those those lovely neko's don't question your wallet or sanity and... just buy it!‚Äù[/i]. With an 18+ certificate, I strongly advise you to keep this purchase and [b][u]play it away from children[/u].[/b]
